Exploring the BRFSS data

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

The primary method of collection of data in this set was through both landline telephone and cellular telelephone-based surveys. With the landline telephone survey, data was collected from a randomly selected adult in a household. In the cellphone-based survey, interviewers collected data from an adult who participated by using a cellphone and resided in a private residence or college housing.

Generalizability - Since the sampled population does not include those individuals who are instititionalized and also does not represent those who do not own a telephone line and cellphone line, there is an issue of a convenience sampling.

Also of importance is the non-response rate for this surveys, the data on the response rate for the 2013 brfss data set can be found here: https://www.cdc.gov/brfss/annual_data/2013/pdf/2013_dqr.pdf

According to the report the median response rate was 46.4% and ranged from 29.0% to 60.3%. The response rate formula used was set by the American Association of Public Opinion Research (AAPOR) Response Rate Formula #4.

Since the average non-response rate is 53.6% and added to the fact the presence of a convenience sample I dont believe it makes much sense to generalize these findings. It may be possible to generalize for certain demographics in the survey if they pass a low enough non-response threshold or if results are also weighted based on the demographic’s specific non-response rate.

Causation - Since the present data is obeservational, we cannot infer any casual associations but can instead only shed light on correlations and associations between variables.

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1:

Considering people that are aged 40yrs to 64 years old - what is the probability that they are in “Excellent” health given that they are retired?

I think most people would like to enter into retirement as soon as they can while still being in good health. I am curious about the health levels of adults who are older than 40 and younger than 65(generally when people are eligible to receive social security) and if their health level and employment status are independent.

Research quesion 2:

Is the Frequency Of Days Now Smoking dependent on what month the survey was taken?

The objective of this question is to see if frequency of smoking for surveyed invidivuals was dependent on what month they were surveyed. My initial guess it is independent of when they are surveyed but it is curious if there is an dependency. Is the Frequency lower in say January because of potential New Years Resolutions perhaps?

Research quesion 3:

Would the variable for # of children in households be a good indicator of an individuals general health level? Which households by # of children have the highest general health levels?

I am curious about the impact on ones health that having children in your household would have. Would it lowest your health possible? Or would you be generally healthier the larger the atomic family you have?

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research quesion 1:

Considering people that are aged 40yrs to 64 years old - what is the probability that they are in “Excellent” health given that they are retired?

We will be working with three specific variables in the dataset to answer this question: general health level(ordinal categorical), Reported Age in Five-Year Age Categories(ordinal categorical) and Employment Status(categorical).

First we will subset our target data into a new dataframe, we will be selecting the data based on people aged 40 to 64 years old.

#creating new data frame with 40-64 year olds in the dataset
brfss_4064 <- brfss2013[brfss2013$X_ageg5yr %in% c("Age 40 to 44","Age 45 to 49","Age 50 to 54","Age 55 to 59","Age 60 to 64"),] 


#changing categorical variables of interest to factors
brfss2013$X_ageg5yr <- as.factor(brfss2013$X_ageg5yr)
brfss2013$employ1 <- as.factor(brfss2013$employ1)
brfss2013$genhlth <- as.factor(brfss2013$genhlth)

brfss_4064$X_ageg5yr <- as.factor(brfss_4064$X_ageg5yr)
brfss_4064$employ1 <- as.factor(brfss_4064$employ1)
brfss_4064$genhlth <- as.factor(brfss_4064$genhlth)

As we can see we Employed for wages makes up the largest % of the early age groups and then starts siginigcant decreasing at Age 60 - 64 as people become eligible for social security benefits. We can also start to see the millenials beginning to bulge at the Age 18-24 mark (to be fair their Age category has the longest length at 6 years).

So we observe that given you are between 40-64 years old and retired, your probability of being in excellent health is 16%. This is lower than those who are Self-Employed(25%), Employed for Wages(20.4%), a Homemaker(20.2%) or a Student(19%). This is a bit unfortunate since I was hoping Americans would be able to retire in good health compared to their counterparts who continue working within the same age group. In fact, those that are retired have a slightly lower probability of being in excellent condition than the whole population of people between 40-64 year olds (16% vs 17%).

So from this are we able to asses that you have a lower chance of being in “Excellent” general health if you choose to retire early instead of working? Well we are unable to definitively make that judgement for the reasons below. Although there is an “Unable to Work” category, it likely does not account for people that don’t consider themselves “Unable to Work” but still choose not to work because of their health and as a result choose to retire early because of their financial security thereby lowering the total general health levels of retirees. Additionally as we can see in the frequency % barplot of the 40-64 year olds below, the largest 5 year group of individuals within the subset are 60-64 year olds. Since they are obviously older and have a higher chance of bad health, they bring the health level down for the whole 40-64 yr old group.

What we can say for sure though is that that Health Level and Employment Status are not independent variables.

#creating new dataset with only retirees between 40-64 years old

So we observe that if you would like to retire between the ages before 64 years old, you would find the highest probability of being in Excellent health if you retire between 40-44 years old (21%). This is the only 5 year bracket of the retiree population from 40-64 years old that rises above the group’s average (17%) This is obviously not too surprising as we expect younger people to have better health levels. We could continue and infer about the healthy retirees in the 40-44 year bracket verses their peers who are not retired yet, but the truth is their sample size is pretty low at only 330 observations, so i do not feel confident in stating that retirees between 40-44 will have a higher probability of being in Excellent health. But at least we can conclude that health levels and employment status are dependent in some way.

Research Question 2

Is an invdividuals Cigarettes smoking frequency independent or dependent on what month the survey was taken?

This question is of interest because although I expect the variables to be independent of each other, I am curious if things like new years resolutions could have decreased smoking habits in January or if the changing of the seasons could have done the same, or if some other event might have increased smoking.

round(prop.table(table(brfss2013$smokday2)),3)
## 
##  Every day  Some days Not at all 
##      0.257      0.100      0.643

With above output from the total population, we observe that: 26% of people smoke everyday 10% smoke some days 64% do not smoke at all.

Let us also take a look at the distribution of when people were surveyed in the data set.

#prob table for what month people were surveyed.
round(prop.table(table(brfss2013$imonth)),3)
## 
##   January  February     March     April       May      June      July 
##     0.070     0.087     0.090     0.087     0.082     0.077     0.089 
##    August September   October  November  December 
##     0.086     0.078     0.086     0.085     0.082
#mean of average surveyed month
round(mean(prop.table(table(brfss2013$imonth))),3)
## [1] 0.083

We observe that on average 8.33% of the population were surveyed each month. With the lowest amount of people being surveyed in January (6.9%), June(7.7%), September(7.8%) with the highest being March(9.0%).

It is a bit unusual that less people were surveyed in January but that could be because the surveyors took vacations then or could not gather survey results for a variety of other reasons. In my opinion the count isnt too low enough to cause any anomalies.

Knowing that the 26% of population smokes everyday and 10% smoke on some days, we can compare it to the relative frequency given the month the inviduals were surveyed to see if they are similar.

#contingency table for relative frequency of smoking habits given month surveyed.
ptab_SmokeMonth <- round(prop.table(table(brfss2013$imonth,brfss2013$smokday2),margin=1),3)
ptab_SmokeMonth
##            
##             Every day Some days Not at all
##   January       0.264     0.103      0.633
##   February      0.258     0.098      0.643
##   March         0.267     0.101      0.632
##   April         0.257     0.101      0.642
##   May           0.261     0.101      0.638
##   June          0.251     0.102      0.647
##   July          0.253     0.101      0.646
##   August        0.259     0.099      0.642
##   September     0.261     0.100      0.639
##   October       0.246     0.100      0.654
##   November      0.252     0.097      0.651
##   December      0.252     0.098      0.649
#(mean,SD) of relative frequency of smoking given user smokes [1]Every day, [2]Some Days, [3]Not at all
c(mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,1])+sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,1])*2,mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,1])-sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,1])*2)
## [1] 0.2689342 0.2445658
c(mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,2])+sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,2])*2,mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,2])-sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,2])*2)
## [1] 0.10364661 0.09652005
c(mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,3])+sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,3])*2,mean(ptab_SmokeMonth[,3])-sd(ptab_SmokeMonth[,3])*2)
## [1] 0.6566182 0.6293818

Below the contingency table are values that represent bounds that we can compare the invidual frequency %’s with. The bounds are defined as 2 standard deviations below the mean and above mean for the Every Day, Some Days and Not at all categories in that order.

The reason for doing this was to confirm that the relative frequencies are all close in value to each other and not out of the ordinary since they all fall within 2 S.Ds from the mean.

If we remember from intial summary statistics, smoking frequency % for the whole population was: Every day Some days Not at all 0.257 0.100 0.643 Since all our relative frequencies are really close to these values, I feel comfortable making the conclusion:

We can confirm independence between the variables Frequency of Smoking and which month the individual was surveyed: P(Smoke Every day | Surveyed in January) = P(Smoke Every day)

As an extra step, we will visualize this in the bar graph below.

#barplot of relative frequency of smoking
ggplot(data=subset(brfss2013,!is.na(imonth)&!is.na(smokday2)), aes(x=smokday2,group=imonth)) + geom_bar(aes(y= ..prop..)) + scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent)+facet_grid(.~imonth) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90,size=12,vjust=-0.1),strip.text.x = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black", angle = 90)) + labs(title="Relative Frequency of Cigarette Smoking given Month individual was surveyed",x="Cigarettes Smoking Freq", y="Relative Frequency %")

If it wasn’t clear before with the contingency table, we can clearly see independence in the graph!

ggplot(data=subset(brfss2013,!is.na(sex)& !is.na(genhlth) & !is.na(X_chldcnt)),aes(x=genhlth,group=sex)) + geom_bar(aes(y=..prop..,fill=factor(..x..)))+ facet_grid(sex~X_chldcnt)+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90,size=12,vjust=0.),strip.text.x = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black", angle = 90),strip.text.y = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black", angle = 0))+labs(title="Relative Probabilities of General Health Level given Gender & # of Children in Household",y="Relative %",x="General Health Level")+scale_fill_discrete(guide=FALSE)

An interesting observation is that the data is telling us that for both males and females, you will have a higher chance of being in Excellent Health given you have more children in your household. Lowest % is in the No Children Category with the highest being in the Five or more Category. I think there are several reasons for this, first in our summary statistic section we noted that 73% of the population have no children currently in their household. This group is massive and can include elderly people in poor health who’ve had their children long ago move from their house, as well as people that have always been in declining health and as a result could not bear children. These factors could be confounding variables as to why the No Children group has the lowest levels of General Health.

Another explanation to why the groups with children have higher health outcomes is that annual income and general wealth might be additional confounding variables, larger families might happen to be in higher income brackets and as a result are able to take care of larger families. Increased wealth could also provide better health outcomes since they would likely have better access to excellent medical services.

Also living in an atomic unit can possibly promote healthier lifestyles because of co-dependence and responsibilities in making the unit work. There is no such pressure on individuals who are not rearing a child since they do not have extra incentive to make sure they are well to take care of another.

Our summary statistic from earlier was as follows for frequency of health outcomes for the entire population: Excellent Very good Good Fair Poor 0.17452786 0.32478409 0.30738684 0.13623390 0.05706731

Based on this and looking at the relative frequencys, I would say the sweet spot would be to have households with 3 children or more, as they all grossly outperform (+20%) the population average(17%). Although general health outcomes and # of children in the household are dependent in some fashion, it seems there are too many other confounding variables like Income and Age and possibly others like Ethnicity and even geographical location to definitively say that # of children in the Household is a good indiciator of general health levels.
